        "p1": {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p>Three years of cracked heels. <strong>My dermatologist warned me off Baby Foot</strong> \u2014 too harsh for my sensitive skin. So I kept my socks on at the beach.</p>"
          }
        },
        "p2": {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p>Then a friend in Seoul sent me a video of a goat milk foot mask. Looked like a cute soft sock filled with white liquid. She said it was the K-beauty answer to harsh peels \u2014 gentler, more hydrating, no peeling, no burning. I ordered one for $25 because I was already $200 deep in things that didn't work.</p>"
          }
        },
        "p_science": {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p><strong>Goat milk's lactic acid is 1/10th the strength of Baby Foot</strong> \u2014 soft enough for sensitive skin, strong enough to work in 30 minutes. No 5-day peeling phase.</p>"
          }
        },
        "p3": {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p>Three weeks later I've used it before every important event \u2014 date nights, my sister's wedding, a beach trip \u2014 and bought the 3-pack so I never run out. The goat milk smell is gentle (none of that fake lavender perfume), the niacinamide visibly evens out the rough patches, and the soft sock shape is genuinely cute enough that I take photos before I put them on. It's the only foot product I've actually used more than once.</p>"
          }
        },
        "p4": {
